*Answer for Question 1)

Given µ= 77.0 and σ = 3.4 and formula for z-score

\[ Z = (x - µ )/σ \]

Applying z-score formula for the questions below

*Answer for Question 1 (a)

      Z = (72.6-77.0)/3.4
      Z = -1.294118
      p(x<72.6) = p(Z<-1.29)
                = 1- F(1.29)
                = 1- 0.9015 , F(1.29) value taken from standard normal table from slides given
                = 0.0985
      p(x<72.6) = p(Z<-1.29) = 0.0985
      In percentage,
      p(x<72.6) = p(Z<-1.29) = 0.0985*100 = 9.85% is the probability of random variable less than 72.6

R Code Result

Approach I
          prob.of.random.var.less.than.72.6 <- (72.6-77.0)/3.4
          print(paste(" ((72.6-77.0)/3.4)  =", prob.of.random.var.less.than.72.6))
## [1] " ((72.6-77.0)/3.4)  = -1.29411764705883"
          print(paste(" Using pnorm function : p(x<72.6)  = ",pnorm(72.6,mean=77.0,sd=3.4)))
## [1] " Using pnorm function : p(x<72.6)  =  0.097812393434633"
Approach II
          randonVariablefun <- function(x,y,z)
         {
             z <- (x-y)/z
             prob <- pnorm(z)
             return(prob)
         }   
         randonVariablefun(72.6,77.0,3.4)
## [1] 0.09781239

*Answer for Question 1 (b)

      Z = (88.5 -77.0)/3.4
      Z = 3.382353
      p(x>88.5) = p(Z>3.38)
                = 1- F(3.38)
                = 1- 0.9996 , F(3.38) value taken from standard normal table
                = 0.0004
      p(x>88.5) = p(Z>3.38) = 0.0004
      In percentage,
      p(x>88.5) = p(Z>3.38) = 0.0004*100 = 0.04% is the probability of random variable greater than 88.5

R Code Result

Approach I
          prob.of.random.var.greater.than.88.5 <- (88.5 -77.0)/3.4
          print(paste(" ((88.5 -77.0)/3.4)  =",prob.of.random.var.greater.than.88.5))
## [1] " ((88.5 -77.0)/3.4)  = 3.38235294117647"
          greater.88.5 <- (1-pnorm(88.5,mean=77.0,sd=3.4))
          print(paste(" Using pnorm function : p(x>88.5)  = ",greater.88.5))
## [1] " Using pnorm function : p(x>88.5)  =  0.000359338725646752"
Approach II
         randonVariablefun <- function(x,y,z)
         {
            z <- (x-y)/z
            prob <- pnorm(z)
            return(prob)
         }
         (1-randonVariablefun(88.5,77.0,3.4))
## [1] 0.0003593387

*Answer for Question 1 (c)

      Z1 = (81-77.0)/3.4
      Z1 = 1.176471
      p(x>81)   = p(Z1>1.17)
                = F(1.17)
                = 0.8790 , F(1.17) value taken from standard normal table
      p(x>81) = p(Z1>1.17) = 0.8790
      Z2 = (84-77.0)/3.4
      Z2 = 2.058824
      p(x<84) = p(Z2<2.05)
              = F(2.05)
              = 0.9798
      p(81<x<84)=p(81<Z<84)
                =F(2.05)-F(1.17)
                =0.9798-0.8790
                =0.1008
      In percentage,
      p(81<x<84)=p(81<Z<84) = 0.1008*100 = 10.08% is the probability of random variable between 81 and 84

R Code Result

Approach I
          prob.of.random.var.between.81.and.84 <- ((84-77.0)/3.4) - ((81-77.0)/3.4)
          print(paste(" ((84-77.0)/3.4) - ((81-77.0)/3.4)  =",prob.of.random.var.between.81.and.84))
## [1] " ((84-77.0)/3.4) - ((81-77.0)/3.4)  = 0.882352941176471"
          print(paste(" Using pnorm function : p(81<x<84) =" ,(pnorm(84,mean=77.0,sd=3.4)-pnorm(81,mean=77.0,sd=3.4))))
## [1] " Using pnorm function : p(81<x<84) = 0.0999478660096137"
Approach II
    randonVariablefun <- function(x1,x2,y,z)
     {
       z1 <- ((x1-y)/z)
       z2 <- ((x2-y)/z)
       prob <- pnorm(z2)-pnorm(z1)
       return(prob)
     }
    randonVariablefun(81,84,77.0,3.4)
## [1] 0.09994787

*Answer for Question 1 (d)

      Z1 = (56-77.0)/3.4
      Z1 = -6.176471
      p(x>56)   = p(Z1>-6.17)
                = F(-6.17)
      Z2 = (92-77.0)/3.4
      Z2 = 4.411765
      p(x<92) = p(Z2<4.41)
              = F(4.41)
      p(56<x<92)=p(56<Z<92)
                =F(4.41)-F(-6.17)
      Values not found from standard normal table assuming 1 or near to it.
      p(56<x<92)=p(56<Z<92) = 1 or 0.99999 is the probability of random variable between 56 and 92

R Code Result

Approach I
          prob.of.random.var.between.56.and.92 <- ((92-77.0)/3.4) - ((56-77.0)/3.4)
          print(paste(" ((92-77.0)/3.4) - ((56-77.0)/3.4)  =",prob.of.random.var.between.56.and.92))
## [1] " ((92-77.0)/3.4) - ((56-77.0)/3.4)  = 10.5882352941176"
          print(paste(" Using pnorm function : p(56<x<92) =" ,(pnorm(92,mean=77.0,sd=3.4)-pnorm(56,mean=77.0,sd=3.4))))
## [1] " Using pnorm function : p(56<x<92) = 0.999994873097099"
Approach II
    randonVariablefun <- function(x1,x2,y,z)
     {
       z1 <- ((x1-y)/z)
       z2 <- ((x2-y)/z)
       prob <- pnorm(z2)-pnorm(z1)
       return(prob)
     }
    randonVariablefun(56,92,77.0,3.4)
## [1] 0.9999949

*Answer for Question 2)

Given µ= 145 and σ = 12 and formula for z-score

\[ Z = (x - µ )/σ \]

*Answer for Question 2 (a)

      Z1 = (130-145)/12
      Z1 = -1.25
      p(x>130) = p(Z1>-1.25)
               = F(-1.25)
               = 1- F(1.25)
               = 1- 0.8944 , F(1.25) value taken from standard normal table
               = 0.1056
      Z2 = (160-145)/12
      Z2 = 1.25
      p(x<160) = p(Z2<1.25)
               = F(1.25) 
               = 0.8944 , F(1.25) value taken from standard normal table
      p(130<x<160) = p(130<Z<160)
                   = F(1.25) - F(-1.25)
                   = 0.8944 - 0.1056
                   = 0.7888
      In percentage,
      p(130<x<160) = p(130<Z<160) = 0.7888*100 = 78.88% is the probability of random variable between 130 and 160 minutes

R Code Result

Approach I
          prob.of.random.var.between.130.and.160 <- ((160-145)/12 - (130-145)/12)
          print(paste(" ((160-145)/12 - (130-145)/12)  =",prob.of.random.var.between.130.and.160))
## [1] " ((160-145)/12 - (130-145)/12)  = 2.5"
          print(paste(" Using pnorm function : p(130<x<160) =" ,(pnorm(160,mean=145,sd=12)-pnorm(130,mean=145,sd=12))*100,"%"))
## [1] " Using pnorm function : p(130<x<160) = 78.8700452666289 %"
Approach II
    randonVariablefun <- function(x1,x2,y,z)
     {
       z1 <- ((x1-y)/z)
       z2 <- ((x2-y)/z)
       prob <- pnorm(z2)-pnorm(z1)
       return(prob)
     }
    randonVariablefun(130,160,145,12)
## [1] 0.7887005

      Z = (130-145)/12

               = 0.1056
      In percentage,
      p(x<130) = p(Z<-1.25) = 0.1056*100 = 10.56% is the probability of random variable less than 130 minutes.

R Code Result

## [1] 0.1056498

*Answer for Question 3)

*Answer for Question 3 (a)

      Two outcomes: True , False
      Probability of question correct : 1/2
      First 5 times : (1/2) * (1/2) * (1/2) * (1/2) * (1/2) = 1/32

R Code Result

         first.five.correct <- (1/2) * (1/2) * (1/2) * (1/2) * (1/2)
         print(paste(" Probability of the student got first five quesions correct ",first.five.correct))
## [1] " Probability of the student got first five quesions correct  0.03125"

*Answer for Question 3 (b)

According to the Binomial Distribution formula,

 p^x         = 0.5^5 = 0.03125
 (1-p)^n-x   = (1-0.5)^(15-5) = 0.00097
 n!/(n-x)!x! = (15!/((15-5)!5!)) = 3003

(15!/((15-5)!5!)) * 0.55(1-0.5)10 = 0.03125 * 0.0009765625 * 3003 = 0.09164429

         print(paste(" The student got five questions correct ",0.03125 * 0.0009765625 * 3003))
## [1] " The student got five questions correct  0.091644287109375"

*Answer for Question 4)

  Mean = (35+42)/2 = 38.5
  Standard deviation = (42-35)/2 = 3.5

R Code Result

          mean <- (35+42)/2
          print(paste(" mean ",mean))
## [1] " mean  38.5"
          Standard.deviation <- (42-35)/2
          print(paste(" Standard.deviation ",Standard.deviation))
## [1] " Standard.deviation  3.5"

*Answer for Question 5)

\[ P(A \mid B) = P(A \cap B)/P(B) \]

\[ P(E1) = 55 \]

\[ P(E2 \cap E1) = 30 \]

\[ P(E2 \mid E1) = 30/55 = 54.54 \]

*Answer for Question 6)

\[ P(A \mid B) = P(A \cap B)/P(B) \]

\[ P(TV) = 82 \]

\[ P(TV \cap DVD) = 62 \]

\[ P(DVD \mid TV) = 62/82 = 75.60976 \]

*Answer for Question 7)

All possibilities , HHH, HHT, HTT, TTT, THH, TTH, THT, HTH

\[ 2^{3} = 8 \]

* 1) All three heads

    HHH
    
    1/8

* 2) Exactly one head

    HTT, TTH, THT
    
    3/8

* 3)

    Exactly one head
    
    HTT, TTH, THT
    
    3/8
    
    Now outcomes 7
    
    Atleast two heads
    
    HHH, HHT, THH, HTH
    
    4/7

*Answer for Question 8)

  Given μ = 90 and σ = 10

  p(x>100) = p(Z>100) = (100-90)/10 = 1 = F(Z>1) = 0.8413
     randonVariablefun <- function(x,y,z)
       {
         z <- (x-y)/z
         prob <- pnorm(z)
         return(prob)
       }   
     randonVariablefun(100,90,10)
## [1] 0.8413447

*Answer for Question 9)

P(A) = Bag1 is from 1994 P(B) = Bag2 is from 1996

the probability that the yellow from both p(A) = p(B) = 1/2

Case 1)

Probability of getting yellow from p(A) = 1/20 = 0.2 Probability of getting green from p(B) = 1/20 = 0.2

Case 2)

Probability of getting green from p(A) = 1/10 = 0.1 Probability of getting yellow from p(B) = 1/140 = 0.14

Then final probability = 0.2 * 0.2 * 0.2+0.2 * 0.1 * 0.14

    0.5 * 0.2 * 0.2+ 0.5 * 0.1 * 0.14
## [1] 0.027

* The relationship between platform and site

     library('ggplot2')
     qplot(x=site,y=platform,data=prob.assignment.dataset)

     library('ggplot2')
     ggplot(aes(x=site,y=platform),data=prob.assignment.dataset)+geom_bar(stat="identity")

* The relationship between Site and orders

     qplot(x=site,y=orders,data=prob.assignment.dataset)

Highest orders recevied from the site Acme.

     ggplot(aes(x=site,y=orders),data=prob.assignment.dataset)+geom_bar(stat="identity",color="gray")

#### *Analysis

Highest orders recevied from the site Acme.

     qplot(x=platform,y=orders,data=prob.assignment.dataset)

* The relationship between orders and gross_sales

    library('dplyr')
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
    orders.groups <- group_by(na.omit(prob.assignment.dataset),orders)
    conditional_mean_by_orders <- summarise(orders.groups, gross_sales_mean = mean(gross_sales),
                                     gross_sales_median = median(gross_sales), n=n())
    head(conditional_mean_by_orders)
## # A tibble: 6 x 4
##   orders gross_sales_mean gross_sales_median     n
##    <dbl>            <dbl>              <dbl> <int>

## 2      1            129.                 99   1510
## 3      2            362.                311    633
## 4      3            598.                537    468
## 5      4            778.                648.   352
## 6      5           1074.                785    317
    ggplot(aes(orders,gross_sales_mean,na.rm=TRUE),data=conditional_mean_by_orders)+geom_point()

    ggplot(aes(orders,gross_sales_mean,na.rm=TRUE),data=conditional_mean_by_orders)+geom_line()

    ggplot(aes(x=orders,y=gross_sales),data=prob.assignment.dataset)+geom_point(alpha=1/20,color='orange')+stat_summary(geom = "line", fun = "mean")
